http://docs.mockito.googlecode.com/hg/1.9.5/org/mockito/ArgumentCaptor.html#forClass(java.lang.Class)

title: Make GPS service foreground to prevent to be killed by the system
message:
Make GPS service foreground to prevent to be killed by the system

http://developer.android.com/guide/components/services.html#Foreground
A foreground service is a service that's considered to be something the user is actively aware of and thus not a candidate for the system to kill when low on memory. A foreground service must provide a notification for the status bar, which is placed under the "Ongoing" heading, which means that the notification cannot be dismissed unless the service is either stopped or removed from the foreground.
For example, a music player that plays music from a service should be set to run in the foreground, because the user is explicitly aware of its operation. The notification in the status bar might indicate the current song and allow the user to launch an activity to interact with the music player.

title: Update PebbleKit to SDK 2.0
message:
Update PebbleKit to SDK 2.0

It should work with both firmware 1.x and 2.x (tested with fw 1.13.0 and 2.0-beta2)
It allows to use 2.x firmware functions (such as getWatchFWVersion), if Exception are correctly catched on firmware 1.x

https://developer.getpebble.com/2/mobile-app-guide/android-guide.html/

PebbleKit Android is distributed in source form as an Android project. Before you can use it in a project, you’ll need to load it into your IDE.

To load it into Eclipse, follow these simple steps:

    Click File –> New Project…
    Select Android Project from Existing Code – Press Next
    Select ~/pebble-dev/PebbleSDK-2.0-BETA2/PebbleKit-Android/PebbleKit as the root directory
    Click Finish

This loadd a new project called PEBBLE_KIT. Ensure there are no errors on this project.

To use PebbleKit Android in one of your Android project:

    Right-click your project and select Properties
    Select the Android pane
    Click Add…
    Select PEBBLE_KIT

That’s it! You can now use PebbleKit in your project.

title: Avoid crash when the activity is killed by the system in extremely low memory situations
message:
Avoid crash when the activity is killed by the system in extremely low memory situations

This is a workaround, waiting for a real fix for the bug.
It should not happen if the GPS is running (foreground service with a sticky notification for the user)
Moreover, it can occur more likely on old devices with little RAM

http://developer.android.com/guide/components/activities.html#Lifecycle

 Make GPS service foreground to prevent to be killed by the system

title: Make GPS service foreground to prevent to be killed by the system
message:
Make GPS service foreground to prevent to be killed by the system

http://developer.android.com/guide/components/services.html#Foreground
A foreground service is a service that's considered to be something the user is actively aware of and thus not a candidate for the system to kill when low on memory. A foreground service must provide a notification for the status bar, which is placed under the "Ongoing" heading, which means that the notification cannot be dismissed unless the service is either stopped or removed from the foreground.
For example, a music player that plays music from a service should be set to run in the foreground, because the user is explicitly aware of its operation. The notification in the status bar might indicate the current song and allow the user to launch an activity to interact with the music player.
